{"title_page": "Environmental issues in the United States", "text_new": "{{See also|Environment of the United States}}\n{{refimprove|date=January 2017}}\n[[Image:GHG per capita 2000.svg|thumb|right|Per capita anthropogenic greenhouse gas emissions by country for the year 2000 including land-use change.]]\n[[File:World CO2 emission by country 2006.svg|thumb|right]]\n'''[[Environmental issues]]''' in the '''[[United States]]''' include climate change, energy, species conservation, invasive species, [[Deforestation in the United States|deforestation]], mining, nuclear accidents, pesticides, pollution, waste and over-population. Despite taking hundreds of measures, the rate of environmental issues is increasing rapidly instead of reducing.\n\n==Movements and ideas==\n{{main|Conservation movement#United States|Conservation in the United States}}\n\n===20th century===\nBoth Conservationism and [[Environmentalism]] appeared in political debate in forests about the [[Progressive Era]] in the early 20th century. There were three main positions. The '''laissez-faire''' position held that owners of private property\u2014including lumber and mining companies, should be allowed to do anything they wished for their property.<ref>Samuelement, 1890-1920'' (1959)</ref>\n\nThe '''Conservationists''', led by President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] and his close ally [[Gifford Pinchot]], said that the laissez-faire approach was too wasteful and inefficient. In any case, they noted, most of the natural resources in the western states were already owned by the federal government.  The best course of action, they argued, was a long-term plan devised by national experts to maximize the long-term economic benefits of natural resources.\n\n'''Environmentalism''' was the third position, led by [[John Muir]] (1838\u20131914). Muir's passion for nature made him the most influential American environmentalist. Muir preached that nature was sacred and humans are intruders who should look but not develop. He founded the [[Sierra Club]] and remains an icon of the environmentalist movement. He was primarily responsible for defining the environmentalist position, in the debate between Conservation and environmentalism.\n\nEnvironmentalism preached that nature was almost sacred, and that man was an intruder. It allowed for limited tourism (such as hiking), but opposed automobiles in national parks. It strenuously opposed timber cutting on most public lands, and vehemently denounced the dams that Roosevelt supported for water supplies, electricity and flood control. Especially controversial was the [[O'Shaughnessy Dam (California)|Hetch Hetchy dam]] in [[Yosemite National Park]], which Roosevelt approved, and which supplies the water supply of San Francisco.\n\n==Climate change==\n{{main|Climate change in the United States}}\nThe United States is the second largest emitter, [[Environment of China|after China]], of [[carbon dioxide]] from the burning of [[fossil fuel]]s.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Vidal, John |author2=David Adam| title=China Overtakes US as World's Biggest CO<sub>2</sub> Emitter | url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2007/jun/19/china.usnews | date=2007-06-19 | accessdate=2007-06-27|work=Guardian}}</ref> The [[energy policy of the United States]] is widely debated; many call on the country to take a leading role in fighting [[global warming]].<ref>{{cite web | title=U.S. Faces International Pressure on Climate Change Policy | url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/environment/july-dec05/climate_7-5.html | date=2005-07-05 | accessdate=2007-05-05| publisher=PBS |work=Online NewsHour}}</ref> The U.S. is one of only three countries that has not signed up to the [[Kyoto Protocol]].\n{{see also|Kyoto protocol#United States}}\n\n===Energy===\n{{main|Energy in the United States}}\n[[Image:Usa night.gif|right|300px|thumb|Satellite image showing the light output at night in the United States]]\n\nSince about 26% of all types of energy used in the United States are derived from [[fossil fuel]] consumption it is closely linked to [[greenhouse gas]] emissions. The energy policy of the United States is determined by federal, state and local public entities, which address issues of energy production, distribution, and consumption, such as building codes and gas mileage advancements. The production and transport of fossil fuels are also tied to significant environmental issues.\n\n==Species conservation==\n{{main|Conservation in the United States}}\nMany plant and animal species became extinct in North America soon after first human arrival, including the [[Pleistocene megafauna#North America|North American megafauna]]; others have become nearly extinct since European settlement, among them the [[American bison]] and [[California condor]].<ref>[http://www.cpluhna.nau.edu/Biota/megafauna_extinctions.htm Pleistocene Megafauna Extinctions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308123523/http://cpluhna.nau.edu/Biota/megafauna_extinctions.htm |date=2010-03-08 }}</ref>\n\nThe last of the [[passenger pigeon]]s died in 1914 after being the most common bird in North America. They were killed as both a source of food and because they were a threat to farming. Saving the [[bald eagle]], the national bird of the U.S., from extinction was a notable conservation success.\n\nAs of 13 December, 2016, the [http://www.iucnredlist.org/ International Union for the Conservation of Nature's Red List] shows the United States has 1,514 species on its Threatened list (Critically Endangered, Endangered and Vulnerable categories).\n\n===Invasive species===\n{{Main|Invasive species in the United States}} Invasive species are a significant problem, some of the most notable being zebra mussels, Burmese pythons, kudzu, brown tree snakes and European starlings. Economic damages are estimated at $120 billion per year.\n\n==Mining==\n{{Main|Mining in the United States}}\n\n==Nuclear==\nThe most notable accident involving [[nuclear power in the United States]] was [[Three Mile Island accident]] in 1979. [[Davis-Besse Nuclear Power Station]] has been the source of two of the top five most dangerous nuclear incidents in the [[United States]] since 1979.<ref>{{cite_web|author=[[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]] |date=2004-09-16 |title=Davis-Besse preliminary accident sequence precursor analysis |format=PDF |url=https://www.nrc.gov/reactors/operating/ops-experience/vessel-head-degradation/news/2004/09-16-04-ml0426005320.pdf |accessdate=2006-06-14 }} and {{cite_web|author=[[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]] |date=2004-09-20 |title=NRC issues preliminary risk analysis of the combined safety issues at Davis-Besse |url=https://www.nrc.gov/reading-rm/doc-collections/news/2004/04-117.html |accessdate=2006-06-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061003054919/http://www.nrc.gov/reading-rm/doc-collections/news/2004/04-117.html |archivedate=2006-10-03 }}</ref>\n\n[[Nuclear safety in the United States]] is governed by federal regulations and continues to be studied by the [[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]] (NRC). The safety of nuclear plants and materials controlled by the U.S. government for research and weapons production, as well those powering naval vessels, is not governed by the NRC.\n\nThe [[anti-nuclear movement in the United States]] consists of more than eighty anti-nuclear groups which have acted to oppose nuclear power and/or [[nuclear weapons]] in the USA. The movement has delayed construction or halted commitments to build some new nuclear plants,<ref name=protest/><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071201005429/http://www.newsday.com/community/guide/lihistory/ny-history-hs9shore,0,563942.story Lights Out at Shoreham: Anti-nuclear activism spurs the closing of a new $6 billion plant] ''Newsday.com'', undated.</ref> and has pressured the [[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]] to enforce and strengthen the safety regulations for nuclear power plants.<ref>Jerry Brown and [[Rinaldo Brutoco]] (1997). ''Profiles in Power: The Anti-nuclear movement and the Dawn of the Solar Age'', p. 198.</ref>   [[Anti-nuclear]] campaigns that captured national public attention in the 1970s and 1980s involved the [[Calvert Cliffs Nuclear Power Plant]], [[Seabrook Station Nuclear Power Plant]], [[Diablo Canyon Power Plant]], [[Shoreham Nuclear Power Plant]], and [[Three Mile Island]].<ref name=protest>Giugni, Marco (2004). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=Kn6YhNtyVigC&pg=PA44&lpg=PA44&dq=shoreham+nuclear+power+plant+protests&source=web&ots=rmz3LVr6tR&sig=sHGK4uiUQ8KKAynuBqZa7NWqYzo  Social Protest and Policy Change: Ecology, Antinuclear, and Peace Movements]'' p. 44.</ref>\n\n==Pesticides==\n{{main|Pesticide use in the United States}}\n[[Pesticide]] use in the United States is predominately by the [[Agriculture in the United States|agricultural sector]], which in 2012 comprised 89% of conventional pesticide usage in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.epa.gov/sites/production/files/2017-01/documents/pesticides-industry-sales-usage-2016_0.pdf|title=US-EPA - Pesticides Industry Sales and Usage 2008-2012|last=|first=|date=|website=EPA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Federal Insecticide, Fungicide, and Rodenticide Act]] (FIFRA) was first passed in 1947, giving the United States Department of Agriculture responsibility for regulating pesticides. In 1972, FIFRA underwent a major revision and transferred responsibility of pesticide regulation to the Environmental Protection Agency and shifted emphasis to protection of the environment and public health.\n\n==Pollution==\n{{main|Pollution in the United States }}\n\n===Air pollution===\n{{main|Air pollution in the United States}}\n\n===Water pollution===\n{{main|Water pollution in the United States}}\n\n===Marine pollution===\n{{see also|Marine pollution|Cruise ship pollution in the United States|Regulation of ship pollution in the United States}}\n\n===Solid and hazardous waste===\n{{main|Hazardous waste in the United States}}\n{{see also|Litter in the United States}}\n\nAt 760&nbsp;kg per person the United States generates the greatest amount of municipal waste.<ref>http://www.nationmaster.com/graph/env_mun_was_gen-environment-municipal-waste-generation Municipal waste generation</ref>\n\n==Population==\n{{main|Population of the United States}}\nThe total U.S. population crossed the 100 million mark around 1915, the 200 million mark in 1967, and the 300 million mark in 2006 (estimated on Tuesday, October 17).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/2005pubs/06statab/pop.pdf |title=Statistical Abstract of the United States |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]}}</ref><ref name=MSNBC_15298443>\n{{cite news \n |title = U.S. population hits 300 million mark\n |url = http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/15298443/\n |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20061017114234/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/15298443/\n |url-status = dead\n |archive-date = 2006-10-17\n |work = [[MSNBC]] ([[Associated Press]])\n |date = 2006-10-17\n |accessdate = 2006-10-17\n}}\n</ref> The U.S. population more than tripled during the 20th century \u2014 a growth rate of about 1.3 percent a year \u2014 from about 76 million in 1900 to 281 million in 2000. This is unlike most [[European countries]], especially [[Germany]], [[Russia]], [[Italy]] and [[Greece]], whose [[Demographics of Europe|populations]] are slowly declining, and whose fertility rates are below replacement.\n\nPopulation growth is fastest among minorities, and according to the [[United States Census Bureau]]'s estimation for 2005, 45% of American children under the age of 5 are minorities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.prb.org/Articles/2006/IntheNewsUSPopulationIsNowOneThirdMinority.aspx?p=1U.S. |title=Population Is Now One-Third Minority |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011081301/http://www.prb.org/Articles/2006/IntheNewsUSPopulationIsNowOneThirdMinority.aspx?p=1U.S. |archivedate=2008-10-11 }}</ref> In 2007, the nation\u2019s minority population reached 102.5 million.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080502050945/http://www.census.gov/Press-Release/www/releases/archives/population/011910.html US Census Press Releases], U.S. Census Bureau</ref> A year before, the minority population totaled 100.7 million. [[Hispanic and Latino Americans]] accounted for almost half (1.4 million) of the national [[population growth]] of 2.9 million between July 1, 2005, and July 1, 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/Press-Release/www/releases/archives/population/010048.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070520055648/http://www.census.gov/Press-Release/www/releases/archives/population/010048.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2007-05-20 |title=U.S. Census Bureau: Minority Population Tops 100 Million }}</ref>\n\nBased on a [[Population Clock|population clock]] maintained by the [[United States Census Bureau|U.S. Census Bureau]], the current U.S. population, as of 5:55 [[Greenwich Mean Time|GMT]] ([[Eastern Time Zone (North America)|EST]]+5) 27 April 2012 is 316,237,337.<ref>{{Cite journal\n|url=https://www.census.gov/main/www/popclock.html\n|title=U.S. Population Clock\n|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau\n|accessdate=2012-04-27\n|postscript=<!--None-->\n|journal=\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110223002408/http://www.census.gov/main/www/popclock.html\n|archive-date=2011-02-23\n|url-status=dead\n}}</ref> A 2004 U.S. Census Bureau report predicted an increase of one third by the year 2050.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/compendia/statab/tables/08s0010.pdf |title=Resident Population Projections by Sex and Age: 2010 to 2050 |accessdate=2008-04-29 |format=[[Portable Document Format|PDF]] (455k) |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528122912/http://www.census.gov/compendia/statab/tables/08s0010.pdf |archivedate=2008-05-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A subsequent 2008 report projects a population of 439 million, which is a 44% increase from 2008.\n\n==Waste==\n{{main|Waste in the United States}}\n{{See also|Electronic waste in the United States}}\n{{see also|Litter in the United States}}\n\n==Conservation and environmental movement==\n{{main|Conservation movement#United States|Environmental movement in the United States}}\nToday, the organized [[environmental movement]] is represented by a wide range of organizations sometimes called [[non-governmental organizations]] or NGOs. These organizations exist on local national and international scales. Environmental NGOs vary widely in political views and in the amount they seek to influence the government. The environmental movement today consists of both large national groups and also many smaller local groups with local concerns. Some resemble the old U.S. conservation movement - whose modern expression is the Nature Conservancy, Audubon Society and National Geographic Society - American organizations with a worldwide influence.\n<!-- to be expanded soon...\n==List of issues==\nComment this sentence out when finished: List current issues not mentioned in the article and are specific to the US only. \nSome current [[environmental issues]] include:\n*[[Mountain top removal]] in the [[Appalachian Mountains]]\n*Deaths of [[tundra swan]]s due to toxic mining wastes in the [[Silver Valley, Idaho]]. <ref>[http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705298235/Toxic-marshes-killing-tundra-swan.html Toxic marshes killing northern Idaho swans]</ref>\n-->\n\n==See also==\n*[[Domestic policy of the George W. Bush administration#Environment|Domestic policy of the George W. Bush administration - Environment]]\n*[[Environmental policy of the Donald Trump administration]]\n*[[List of environmental issues]]\n*[[Mountaintop removal mining]]\n*[[MTBE controversy]]\n*[[Recycling in the United States]]\n*[[United States offshore drilling debate]]\n*[[Water pollution in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bates, J. Leonard.  \"Fulfilling American Democracy: The Conservation Movement, 1907 to 1921\", ''The Mississippi Valley Historical Review,'' (1957), 44#1 pp.&nbsp;29\u201357. [https://www.jstor.org/pss/1898667 in JSTOR]\n* Brinkley, Douglas G. ''The Wilderness Warrior: Theodore Roosevelt and the Crusade for America,'' (2009) [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0060565314/  excerpt and text search]\n* Cawley, R. McGreggor. ''Federal Land, Western Anger: The Sagebrush Rebellion and Environmental Politics'' (1993), on conservatives\n* Flippen, J. Brooks. ''Nixon and the Environment'' (2000).\n* Hays, Samuel P. ''Beauty, Health, and Permanence: Environmental Politics in the United States, 1955\u20131985'' (1987), the standard scholarly history\n** Hays, Samuel P. ''A History of Environmental Politics since 1945'' (2000), shorter standard history\n* King, Judson. ''The Conservation Fight, From Theodore Roosevelt to the Tennessee Valley Authority'' (2009)\n* Nash, Roderick. ''Wilderness and the American Mind,'' (3rd ed. 1982), the standard intellectual history\n* Rothman,  Hal K. ''The Greening of a Nation? Environmentalism in the United States since 1945'' (1998)\n* Scheffer, Victor B. ''The Shaping of Environmentalism in America'' (1991).\n* Sellers, Christopher. ''Crabgrass Crucible: Suburban Nature and the Rise of Environmentalism in Twentieth-Century America'' (2012)\n* Strong, Douglas H.  ''Dreamers & Defenders: American Conservationists.'' (1988) [https://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&d=8516594 online edition], good biographical studies of the major leaders\n* Turner, James Morton, \"The Specter of Environmentalism\": Wilderness, Environmental Politics, and the Evolution of the New Right. ''The Journal of American History'' 96.1 (2009): 123-47 [https://web.archive.org/web/20090703095241/http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/jah/96.1/turner.html online at History Cooperative]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081105053529/http://www.lowimpactliving.com/pages/impact-calculator/impact-calculator Calculate the ecological footprint of your household: Low Impact Living]\n\n{{United States topic|prefix=Environmental issues in}}\n{{North America in topic|Environmental issues in}}\n{{Portal bar|Environment|United States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Environmental Issues In The United States}}\n[[Category:Environmental issues in the United States| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{See also|Environment of the United States}}\n{{refimprove|date=January 2017}}\n[[Image:GHG per capita 2000.svg|thumb|right|Per capita anthropogenic greenhouse gas emissions by country for the year 2000 including land-use change.]]\n[[File:World CO2 emission by country 2006.svg|thumb|right]]\n'''[[Environmental issues]]''' in the '''[[United States]]''' include climate change, energy, species conservation, invasive species, [[Deforestation in the United States|deforestation]], mining, nuclear accidents, pesticides, pollution, waste and over-population. Despite taking hundreds of measures, the rate of environmental issues is increasing rapidly instead of reducing.\n\n==Movements and ideas==\n{{main|Conservation movement#United States|Conservation in the United States}}\n\n===20th century===\nBoth Conservationism and [[Environmentalism]] appeared in political debate in forests about the [[Progressive Era]] in the early 20th century. There were three main positions. The '''laissez-faire''' position held that owners of private property\u2014including lumber and mining companies, should be allowed to do anything they wished for their property.<ref>Samuelement, 1890-1920'' (1959)</ref>\n\nThe '''Conservationists''', led by President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] and his close ally [[Gifford Pinchot]], said that the laissez-faire approach was too wasteful and inefficient. In any case, they noted, most of the natural resources in the western states were already owned by the federal government.  The best course of action, they argued, was a long-term plan devised by national experts to maximize the long-term economic benefits of natural resources.\n\n'''Environmentalism''' was the third position, led by [[John Muir]] (1838\u20131914). Muir's passion for nature made him the most influential American environmentalist. Muir preached that nature was sacred and humans are intruders who should look but not develop. He founded the [[Sierra Club]] and remains an icon of the environmentalist movement. He was primarily responsible for defining the environmentalist position, in the debate between Conservation and environmentalism.\n\nEnvironmentalism preached that nature was almost sacred, and that man was an intruder. It allowed for limited tourism (such as hiking), but opposed automobiles in national parks. It strenuously opposed timber cutting on most public lands, and vehemently denounced the dams that Roosevelt supported for water supplies, electricity and flood control. Especially controversial was the [[O'Shaughnessy Dam (California)|Hetch Hetchy dam]] in [[Yosemite National Park]], which Roosevelt approved, and which supplies the water supply of San Francisco.\n\n==Climate change==\n{{main|Climate change in the United States}}\nThe United States is the second largest emitter, [[Environment of China|after China]], of [[carbon dioxide]] from the burning of [[fossil fuel]]s.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Vidal, John |author2=David Adam| title=China Overtakes US as World's Biggest CO<sub>2</sub> Emitter | url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2007/jun/19/china.usnews | date=2007-06-19 | accessdate=2007-06-27|work=Guardian}}</ref> The [[energy policy of the United States]] is widely debated; many call on the country to take a leading role in fighting [[global warming]].<ref>{{cite web | title=U.S. Faces International Pressure on Climate Change Policy | url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/environment/july-dec05/climate_7-5.html | date=2005-07-05 | accessdate=2007-05-05| publisher=PBS |work=Online NewsHour}}</ref> The U.S. is one of only three countries that has not signed up to the [[Kyoto Protocol]].\n{{see also|Kyoto protocol#United States}}\n\n===Energy===\n{{main|Energy in the United States}}\n[[Image:Usa night.gif|right|300px|thumb|Satellite image showing the light output at night in the United States]]\n\nSince about 26% of all types of energy used in the United States are derived from [[fossil fuel]] consumption it is closely linked to [[greenhouse gas]] emissions. The energy policy of the United States is determined by federal, state and local public entities, which address issues of energy production, distribution, and consumption, such as building codes and gas mileage advancements. The production and transport of fossil fuels are also tied to significant environmental issues.\n\n==Species conservation==\n{{main|Conservation in the United States}}\nMany plant and animal species became extinct in North America soon after first human arrival, including the [[Pleistocene megafauna#North America|North American megafauna]]; others have become nearly extinct since European settlement, among them the [[American bison]] and [[California condor]].<ref>[http://www.cpluhna.nau.edu/Biota/megafauna_extinctions.htm Pleistocene Megafauna Extinctions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308123523/http://cpluhna.nau.edu/Biota/megafauna_extinctions.htm |date=2010-03-08 }}</ref>\n\nThe last of the [[passenger pigeon]]s died in 1914 after being the most common bird in North America. They were killed as both a source of food and because they were a threat to farming. Saving the [[bald eagle]], the national bird of the U.S., from extinction was a notable conservation success.\n\nAs of 13 December, 2016, the [http://www.iucnredlist.org/ International Union for the Conservation of Nature's Red List] shows the United States has 1,514 species on its Threatened list (Critically Endangered, Endangered and Vulnerable categories).\n\n===Invasive species===\n{{Main|Invasive species in the United States}} Invasive species are a significant problem, some of the most notable being zebra mussels, Burmese pythons, kudzu, brown tree snakes and European starlings. Economic damages are estimated at $120 billion per year.\n\n==Mining==\n{{Main|Mining in the United States}}\n\n==Nuclear==\nThe most notable accident involving [[nuclear power in the United States]] was [[Three Mile Island accident]] in 1979. [[Davis-Besse Nuclear Power Station]] has been the source of two of the top five most dangerous nuclear incidents in the [[United States]] since 1979.<ref>{{cite_web|author=[[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]] |date=2004-09-16 |title=Davis-Besse preliminary accident sequence precursor analysis |format=PDF |url=https://www.nrc.gov/reactors/operating/ops-experience/vessel-head-degradation/news/2004/09-16-04-ml0426005320.pdf |accessdate=2006-06-14 }} and {{cite_web|author=[[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]] |date=2004-09-20 |title=NRC issues preliminary risk analysis of the combined safety issues at Davis-Besse |url=https://www.nrc.gov/reading-rm/doc-collections/news/2004/04-117.html |accessdate=2006-06-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061003054919/http://www.nrc.gov/reading-rm/doc-collections/news/2004/04-117.html |archivedate=2006-10-03 }}</ref>\n\n[[Nuclear safety in the United States]] is governed by federal regulations and continues to be studied by the [[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]] (NRC). The safety of nuclear plants and materials controlled by the U.S. government for research and weapons production, as well those powering naval vessels, is not governed by the NRC.\n\nThe [[anti-nuclear movement in the United States]] consists of more than eighty anti-nuclear groups which have acted to oppose nuclear power and/or [[nuclear weapons]] in the USA. The movement has delayed construction or halted commitments to build some new nuclear plants,<ref name=protest/><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071201005429/http://www.newsday.com/community/guide/lihistory/ny-history-hs9shore,0,563942.story Lights Out at Shoreham: Anti-nuclear activism spurs the closing of a new $6 billion plant] ''Newsday.com'', undated.</ref> and has pressured the [[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]] to enforce and strengthen the safety regulations for nuclear power plants.<ref>Jerry Brown and [[Rinaldo Brutoco]] (1997). ''Profiles in Power: The Anti-nuclear movement and the Dawn of the Solar Age'', p. 198.</ref>   [[Anti-nuclear]] campaigns that captured national public attention in the 1970s and 1980s involved the [[Calvert Cliffs Nuclear Power Plant]], [[Seabrook Station Nuclear Power Plant]], [[Diablo Canyon Power Plant]], [[Shoreham Nuclear Power Plant]], and [[Three Mile Island]].<ref name=protest>Giugni, Marco (2004). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=Kn6YhNtyVigC&pg=PA44&lpg=PA44&dq=shoreham+nuclear+power+plant+protests&source=web&ots=rmz3LVr6tR&sig=sHGK4uiUQ8KKAynuBqZa7NWqYzo  Social Protest and Policy Change: Ecology, Antinuclear, and Peace Movements]'' p. 44.</ref>\n\n==Pesticides==\n{{main|Pesticide use in the United States}}\n[[Pesticide]] use in the United States is predominately by the [[Agriculture in the United States|agricultural sector]] and about a quarter of pesticides used are used in houses, yards, parks, golf courses, and swimming pools.{{citation needed|date=May 2012}}\n\nThe [[Federal Insecticide, Fungicide, and Rodenticide Act]] (FIFRA) was first passed in 1947, giving the United States Department of Agriculture responsibility for regulating pesticides. In 1972, FIFRA underwent a major revision and transferred responsibility of pesticide regulation to the Environmental Protection Agency and shifted emphasis to protection of the environment and public health.\n\n==Pollution==\n{{main|Pollution in the United States }}\n\n===Air pollution===\n{{main|Air pollution in the United States}}\n\n===Water pollution===\n{{main|Water pollution in the United States}}\n\n===Marine pollution===\n{{see also|Marine pollution|Cruise ship pollution in the United States|Regulation of ship pollution in the United States}}\n\n===Solid and hazardous waste===\n{{main|Hazardous waste in the United States}}\n{{see also|Litter in the United States}}\n\nAt 760&nbsp;kg per person the United States generates the greatest amount of municipal waste.<ref>http://www.nationmaster.com/graph/env_mun_was_gen-environment-municipal-waste-generation Municipal waste generation</ref>\n\n==Population==\n{{main|Population of the United States}}\nThe total U.S. population crossed the 100 million mark around 1915, the 200 million mark in 1967, and the 300 million mark in 2006 (estimated on Tuesday, October 17).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/2005pubs/06statab/pop.pdf |title=Statistical Abstract of the United States |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]}}</ref><ref name=MSNBC_15298443>\n{{cite news \n |title = U.S. population hits 300 million mark\n |url = http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/15298443/\n |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20061017114234/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/15298443/\n |url-status = dead\n |archive-date = 2006-10-17\n |work = [[MSNBC]] ([[Associated Press]])\n |date = 2006-10-17\n |accessdate = 2006-10-17\n}}\n</ref> The U.S. population more than tripled during the 20th century \u2014 a growth rate of about 1.3 percent a year \u2014 from about 76 million in 1900 to 281 million in 2000. This is unlike most [[European countries]], especially [[Germany]], [[Russia]], [[Italy]] and [[Greece]], whose [[Demographics of Europe|populations]] are slowly declining, and whose fertility rates are below replacement.\n\nPopulation growth is fastest among minorities, and according to the [[United States Census Bureau]]'s estimation for 2005, 45% of American children under the age of 5 are minorities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.prb.org/Articles/2006/IntheNewsUSPopulationIsNowOneThirdMinority.aspx?p=1U.S. |title=Population Is Now One-Third Minority |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011081301/http://www.prb.org/Articles/2006/IntheNewsUSPopulationIsNowOneThirdMinority.aspx?p=1U.S. |archivedate=2008-10-11 }}</ref> In 2007, the nation\u2019s minority population reached 102.5 million.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080502050945/http://www.census.gov/Press-Release/www/releases/archives/population/011910.html US Census Press Releases], U.S. Census Bureau</ref> A year before, the minority population totaled 100.7 million. [[Hispanic and Latino Americans]] accounted for almost half (1.4 million) of the national [[population growth]] of 2.9 million between July 1, 2005, and July 1, 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/Press-Release/www/releases/archives/population/010048.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070520055648/http://www.census.gov/Press-Release/www/releases/archives/population/010048.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2007-05-20 |title=U.S. Census Bureau: Minority Population Tops 100 Million }}</ref>\n\nBased on a [[Population Clock|population clock]] maintained by the [[United States Census Bureau|U.S. Census Bureau]], the current U.S. population, as of 5:55 [[Greenwich Mean Time|GMT]] ([[Eastern Time Zone (North America)|EST]]+5) 27 April 2012 is 316,237,337.<ref>{{Cite journal\n|url=https://www.census.gov/main/www/popclock.html\n|title=U.S. Population Clock\n|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau\n|accessdate=2012-04-27\n|postscript=<!--None-->\n|journal=\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110223002408/http://www.census.gov/main/www/popclock.html\n|archive-date=2011-02-23\n|url-status=dead\n}}</ref> A 2004 U.S. Census Bureau report predicted an increase of one third by the year 2050.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/compendia/statab/tables/08s0010.pdf |title=Resident Population Projections by Sex and Age: 2010 to 2050 |accessdate=2008-04-29 |format=[[Portable Document Format|PDF]] (455k) |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528122912/http://www.census.gov/compendia/statab/tables/08s0010.pdf |archivedate=2008-05-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A subsequent 2008 report projects a population of 439 million, which is a 44% increase from 2008.\n\n==Waste==\n{{main|Waste in the United States}}\n{{See also|Electronic waste in the United States}}\n{{see also|Litter in the United States}}\n\n==Conservation and environmental movement==\n{{main|Conservation movement#United States|Environmental movement in the United States}}\nToday, the organized [[environmental movement]] is represented by a wide range of organizations sometimes called [[non-governmental organizations]] or NGOs. These organizations exist on local national and international scales. Environmental NGOs vary widely in political views and in the amount they seek to influence the government. The environmental movement today consists of both large national groups and also many smaller local groups with local concerns. Some resemble the old U.S. conservation movement - whose modern expression is the Nature Conservancy, Audubon Society and National Geographic Society - American organizations with a worldwide influence.\n<!-- to be expanded soon...\n==List of issues==\nComment this sentence out when finished: List current issues not mentioned in the article and are specific to the US only. \nSome current [[environmental issues]] include:\n*[[Mountain top removal]] in the [[Appalachian Mountains]]\n*Deaths of [[tundra swan]]s due to toxic mining wastes in the [[Silver Valley, Idaho]]. <ref>[http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705298235/Toxic-marshes-killing-tundra-swan.html Toxic marshes killing northern Idaho swans]</ref>\n-->\n\n==See also==\n*[[Domestic policy of the George W. Bush administration#Environment|Domestic policy of the George W. Bush administration - Environment]]\n*[[Environmental policy of the Donald Trump administration]]\n*[[List of environmental issues]]\n*[[Mountaintop removal mining]]\n*[[MTBE controversy]]\n*[[Recycling in the United States]]\n*[[United States offshore drilling debate]]\n*[[Water pollution in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bates, J. Leonard.  \"Fulfilling American Democracy: The Conservation Movement, 1907 to 1921\", ''The Mississippi Valley Historical Review,'' (1957), 44#1 pp.&nbsp;29\u201357. [https://www.jstor.org/pss/1898667 in JSTOR]\n* Brinkley, Douglas G. ''The Wilderness Warrior: Theodore Roosevelt and the Crusade for America,'' (2009) [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0060565314/  excerpt and text search]\n* Cawley, R. McGreggor. ''Federal Land, Western Anger: The Sagebrush Rebellion and Environmental Politics'' (1993), on conservatives\n* Flippen, J. Brooks. ''Nixon and the Environment'' (2000).\n* Hays, Samuel P. ''Beauty, Health, and Permanence: Environmental Politics in the United States, 1955\u20131985'' (1987), the standard scholarly history\n** Hays, Samuel P. ''A History of Environmental Politics since 1945'' (2000), shorter standard history\n* King, Judson. ''The Conservation Fight, From Theodore Roosevelt to the Tennessee Valley Authority'' (2009)\n* Nash, Roderick. ''Wilderness and the American Mind,'' (3rd ed. 1982), the standard intellectual history\n* Rothman,  Hal K. ''The Greening of a Nation? Environmentalism in the United States since 1945'' (1998)\n* Scheffer, Victor B. ''The Shaping of Environmentalism in America'' (1991).\n* Sellers, Christopher. ''Crabgrass Crucible: Suburban Nature and the Rise of Environmentalism in Twentieth-Century America'' (2012)\n* Strong, Douglas H.  ''Dreamers & Defenders: American Conservationists.'' (1988) [https://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&d=8516594 online edition], good biographical studies of the major leaders\n* Turner, James Morton, \"The Specter of Environmentalism\": Wilderness, Environmental Politics, and the Evolution of the New Right. ''The Journal of American History'' 96.1 (2009): 123-47 [https://web.archive.org/web/20090703095241/http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/jah/96.1/turner.html online at History Cooperative]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081105053529/http://www.lowimpactliving.com/pages/impact-calculator/impact-calculator Calculate the ecological footprint of your household: Low Impact Living]\n\n{{United States topic|prefix=Environmental issues in}}\n{{North America in topic|Environmental issues in}}\n{{Portal bar|Environment|United States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Environmental Issues In The United States}}\n[[Category:Environmental issues in the United States| ]]\n", "name_user": "Stompypuppy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePesticides:Added citation. Slight modification to language.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Environmental_issues_in_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "John Docherty (footballer, born 1940)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = John Docherty\n| fullname = \n| image = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1940|4|29|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| death_date  = \n| height = \n| position = [[Right winger]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 =\n| years1 =\n| years2 = 1959\u20131961\n| clubs1 = [[St Roch's F.C.|St Roch's]]\n| clubs2 = [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]\n| caps1 =  \n| caps2 = 17\n| goals1 =  \n| goals2 = 2\n|caps3 =41 |years3 =1961\u20131966 |goals3 =9 |clubs3 = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]|caps4 = 97|goals4 = 31|years4 = 1966\u20131968|clubs4 = [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]|clubs5 = [[Reading F.C.|Reading]]|years5 = 1968\u20131970|goals5 = 8|caps5 = 46|clubs6 = [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]|years6 = 1970\u20131974|caps6 = 116|goals6 = 33|clubs7 = [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]]|years7 = 1974\u20131975|goals7 = 0|caps7 = 0\n|manageryears1 = 1975\u20131976\n|managerclubs1 = [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]\n|manageryears2 = 1978\u20131983\n|managerclubs2 = [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]]\n|manageryears3 = 1986\u20131990\n|managerclubs3 = [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]\n|manageryears4 = 1990\u20131991\n|managerclubs4 = [[Bradford City F.C.|Bradford City]]\n|manageryears5 = 1997\n|managerclubs5 = [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]\n|totalcaps = 317|totalgoals = 116}}\n\n'''John Docherty''' (born 29 April 1940) is a Scottish former football player and manager.\n\n== Managerial career ==\nHaving previously been manager of [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]] between January 1978 and 13 December 1983 and [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = League Managers Association - John Docherty|url = http://www.leaguemanagers.com/managers/john-docherty/|website = www.leaguemanagers.com|accessdate = 2015-10-19}}</ref> and briefly coaching at The St Clement Danes Boys Grammar School after leaving Brentford, his spell at Cambridge United saw the club in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] where they managed respectable finishes, with eighth in [[1979\u201380 Football League|1979\u201380]] being their highest.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Football Club History Database - Cambridge United|url = http://www.fchd.info/CAMBRIDU.HTM|website = www.fchd.info|accessdate = 2015-10-19}}</ref> The following season saw the side as outside contenders for promotion before a late slump saw them finish 13th.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Cambridge United Home Page for the 1980-1981 season - Statto.com|url = http://www.statto.com/football/teams/cambridge-united/1980-1981|website = Statto.com|accessdate = 2015-10-19}}</ref>\n\nHe was appointed Millwall manager in May 1986 following the departure of [[George Graham (footballer)|George Graham]] to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref name=\":0\" /> In his second season as manager, he guided them to the Second Division title and gained Millwall their first top division campaign.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDocherty's team performed well in the first half of the 1988\u201389 season, topping the table at one point. Their form in the second half of the season faded, and their position of 10th place in the final table was their lowest standing all season,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Millwall Home Page for the 1988-1989 season - Statto.com|url = http://www.statto.com/football/teams/millwall/1988-1989|website = Statto.com|accessdate = 2015-10-19}}</ref> but still, this remains their highest league finishing position to date.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Football Club History Database - Millwall|url = http://fchd.info/MILLWALL.HTM|website = fchd.info|accessdate = 2015-10-19}}</ref>\n\nThe 1989\u201390 season started well for Millwall, and they again briefly topped the league in September, but won only two more league games all season and were relegated in bottom place.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Millwall Home Page for the 1989-1990 season - Statto.com|url = http://www.statto.com/football/teams/millwall/1989-1990|website = Statto.com|accessdate = 2015-10-19}}</ref> Just before relegation was confirmed, Docherty was dismissed in favour of [[Bruce Rioch]] in February 1990.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title = John Docherty {{!}} Latest Betting Odds {{!}} Soccer Base|url = http://www.soccerbase.com/managers/manager.sd?manager_id=798|website = www.soccerbase.com|accessdate = 2015-10-19}}</ref>\n\nDocherty's next stop was at [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]], in March 1990,<ref name=\":1\" /> who were relegated to the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] later that season.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Bradford City Home Page for the 1989-1990 season - Statto.com|url = http://www.statto.com/football/teams/bradford-city/1989-1990|website = Statto.com|accessdate = 2015-10-19}}</ref> He was in charge for 20 months before being sacked on 11 November 1991, to make way for [[Frank Stapleton]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDocherty returned to Millwall during the [[1996-97 in English football|1996\u201397]] season,<ref name=\":0\" /> but by this stage they were in the new Division Two (the third flight of English football) and he failed to emulate his first spell as manager.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Millwall Home Page for the 1996-1997 season - Statto.com|url = http://www.statto.com/football/teams/millwall/1996-1997|website = Statto.com|accessdate = 2015-10-19}}</ref> His contract was not renewed at the end of the season and he was replaced by [[Billy Bonds]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nDochety now lives in retirement in [[Wiltshire]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Wally meets...the manager who put Dean Richards on the road top the big time, John Docherty|url = https://www.mirror.co.uk/opinion/football-opinion/exclusive-interview-boss-who-put-3331235|website = mirror|accessdate = 2015-10-19}}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n'''[[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]'''\n* [[Football League Fourth Division]] third-place promotion: [[1971\u201372 Brentford F.C. season|1971\u201372]]<ref name=\"White\">{{Cite book|title=100 Years Of Brentford|last=|first=|publisher=Brentford FC|year=1989|isbn=0951526200|editor-last=White|editor-first=Eric|location=|pages=391|via=}}</ref>\n* [[Millwall]]\n* Football League 2nd Division Champions 1988\n* \n* References\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{NeilBrownPlayers|player/johndocherty}}\n*{{soccerbase (manager)|798|John Docherty}}\n{{Brentford F.C. Player of the Year}}{{Brentford F.C. managers}}\n{{Cambridge United F.C. managers}}\n{{Millwall F.C. managers}}\n{{Bradford City A.F.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Docherty, John}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish football managers]]\n[[Category:Cambridge United F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Brentford F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Millwall F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Brentford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Reading F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:St Roch's F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Queens Park Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Brentford F.C. non-playing staff]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = John Docherty\n| fullname = \n| image = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1940|4|29|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date  = \n| height = \n| position = [[Right winger]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 =\n| years1 =\n| years2 = 1959\u20131961\n| clubs1 = [[St Roch's F.C.|St Roch's]]\n| clubs2 = [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]\n| caps1 =  \n| caps2 = 17\n| goals1 =  \n| goals2 = 2\n|caps3 =41 |years3 =1961\u20131966 |goals3 =9 |clubs3 = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]|caps4 = 97|goals4 = 31|years4 = 1